V(English) I was born in a middle class family.
p6
aVMy father was five years old when he lost his father,
p7
aVbut by the time I was born,
p8
aVhe was already a businessman.
p9
aVBut it didn't make a difference to him
p10
aVif his children were going to be a boy or a girl:
p11
aVthey were going to go to school.
p12
aVSo I guess I was the lucky one.
p13
aa(lp14
VMy mother had 16 pregnancies.
p15
aVFrom 16 pregnancies, five of us are alive.
p16
aVYou can imagine as a child what I went through.
p17
aVDay to day, I watched women
p18
aVbeing carried to a graveyard,
p19
aVor watched children going to a graveyard.
p20
aVAt that time, when I finished my high school,
p21
aVI really wanted to be a doctor.
p22
aVI wanted to be a doctor to help women and children.
p23
aVSo I completed my education,
p24
aVbut I wanted to go to university.
p25
aVUnfortunately, in my country, there wasn't a dormitory for girls,
p26
aVso I was accepted in medical school, but I could not go there.
p27
aVSo as a result, my father sent me to America.
p28
aa(lp29
VI came to America.
p30
aVI completed my education.
p31
aVWhile I was completing my education,
p32
aVmy country was invaded by Russia.
p33
aVAnd do you know that at the time I was completing my education,
p34
aVI didn't know what was going on with my family or with my country.
p35
aVThere were months, years, I didn't know about it.
p36
aVMy family was in a refugee camp.
p37
aVSo as soon as I completed my education,
p38
aVI brought my family to America.
p39
aVI wanted them to be safe.
p40
aa(lp41
VBut where was my heart?
p42
aVMy heart was in Afghanistan.
p43
aVDay after day, when I listened to the news,
p44
aVwhen I followed what was going on with my country,
p45
aVmy heart was breaking up.
p46
aVI really wanted to go back to my country,
p47
aVbut at the same time I knew I could not go there,
p48
aVbecause there was no place for me.
p49
aVI had a good job.
p50
aVI was a professor at a university.
p51
aVI earned good money.
p52
aVI had a good life.
p53
aVMy family was here.
p54
aVI could live with them.
p55
aVBut I wasn't happy.
p56
aVI wanted to go back home.
p57
aVSo I went to the refugee camp.
p58
aVAnd when I went to the refugee camp in Pakistan,
p59
aVthere were 7.5 million refugees.
p60
aV7.5 million refugees.
p61
aVAbout 90 percent of them were women and children.
p62
aVMost of the men have been killed or they were in war.
p63
aVAnd you know, in the refugee camp,
p64
aVwhen I went day-to-day to do a survey,
p65
aVI found things you never could imagine.
p66
aVI saw a widow with five to eight children
p67
aVsitting there and weeping
p68
aVand not knowing what to do.
p69
aVI saw a young woman have no way to go anywhere,
p70
aVno education, no entertainment, no place to even live.
p71
aVI saw young men that had lost their father and their home,
p72
aVand they are supporting the family as a 10-to-12-year old boy \u2014
p73
aVbeing the head of the household,
p74
aVtrying to protect their sister and their mother and their children.
p75
aa(lp76
VSo it was a very devastating situation.
p77
aVMy heart was beating for my people,
p78
aVand I didn't know what to do.
p79
aVAt that moment, we talk about momentum.
p80
aVAt that moment, I felt, what can I do for these people?
p81
aVHow could I help these people?
p82
aVI am one individual. What can I do for them?
p83
aa(lp84
VBut at that moment, I knew
p85
aVthat education changed my life.
p86
aVIt transformed me. It gave me status.
p87
aVIt gave me confidence. It gave me a career.
p88
aVIt helped me to support my family,
p89
aVto bring my family to another country,
p90
aVto be safe.
p91
aVAnd I knew that at that moment
p92
aVthat what I should give to my people is education and health,
p93
aVand that's what I went after.
