aa(lp95
VBut do you think it was easy?
p96
aVNo, because at that time, education was banned for girls, completely.
p97
aVAnd also, by Russia invading Afghanistan,
p98
aVpeople were not trusting anyone.
p99
aVIt was very hard to come and say, "I want to do this."
p100
aVWho am I?
p101
aVSomebody who comes from the United States.
p102
aVSomebody who got educated here.
p103
aVDid they trust me? Of course not.
p104
aa(lp105
VSo I really needed to build the trust in this community.
p106
aVHow am I going to do that?
p107
aVI went and surveyed and looked and looked.
p108
aVI asked.
p109
aVFinally, I found one man.
p110
aVHe was 80 years old.
p111
aVHe was a mullah.
p112
aVI went to his tent in the camp,
p113
aVand I asked him,
p114
aV"I want to make you a teacher."
p115
aVAnd he looked at me,
p116
aVand he said, "Crazy woman,
p117
aVcrazy woman, how do you think I can be a teacher?"
p118
aVAnd I told him, "I will make you a teacher."
p119
aVFinally, he accepted my offer,
p120
aVand once I started a class in his compound,
p121
aVthe word spread all over.
p122
aVIn a matter of one year,
p123
aVwe had 25 schools set up,
p124
aV15,000 children going to school,
p125
aVand it was amazing.
